`msg.Ack` or `msg.Nack` within the Receive handler function. This is necessary to ensure proper flow control and guarantees messages are ack'ed (or nacked) when the Receive function is cancelled for any reason. 

This PR removes the use of channels to handle messages and removes synchronization (aside from `atomic` adds) within the samples, which can confuse users who don't know that this is only for testing purposes to avoid race conditions. I also added a comment stating that the context timeout is only for helping testing, and should _not_ be used for production code.

Lastly, refactor the tests so that only one message is published. We aren't testing complex client library functionality with these samples, and only publishing one message gets around race conditions when calling `fmt.Fprintf` inside the Receive handler.
